  "response": "The distinction between an \"innie\" and an \"outie\" belly button is purely cosmetic. There are **no medical advantages or disadvantages** associated with having one or the other. Your belly button type doesn't affect your health, fitness, or lifespan.\n\nHere's a breakdown of why they exist and some common misconceptions:\n\n*   **How they form:** After birth, the umbilical cord is clamped and cut. What remains is a small stump. As the stump heals, the skin pulls inwards, typically creating an \"innie.\" An \"outie\" occurs when the scar tissue protrudes slightly outwards instead of retracting. It's often a result of how the umbilical cord was cut or how the area healed.\n\n*   **Misconceptions:** Some people believe that an outie is a sign of a difficult birth or a weak abdominal wall. This is entirely false. The shape of your belly button is simply a quirk of the healing process.\n\n**In summary:** Don't worry about whether you have an innie or an outie. It's a cosmetic feature that has no bearing on your health or well-being.\n",
